<HEADLINE>
<P>
CUSTODY FIGHT BLAMED AS WOMAN KILLS DAUGHTER, 3, THEN HERSELF 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By AARON CURTISS, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A woman who feared that her estranged husband would gain custody of their 
3-year-old daughter shot and killed the girl and then herself Wednesday as they 
rode in a friend's camper in Panorama City, Los Angeles police said. 
</P>
<P>
Josephina Rios, 29, died about 10:15 p.m., four hours after she fired a single 
round into the head of her daughter, Samantha, and then shot herself in the 
head, Sgt. Joe Braza said. 
</P>
<P>
Investigators found a one-page note apparently written by Rios saying that she 
was despondent over the prospect of her husband gaining custody of their 
daughter. 
</P>
<P>
Detective Mike Houchen said Rios feared that her husband, Antonio Rios, would 
disappear with the child. The couple, who lived in Anaheim, had been separated 
for about a year and were going through a divorce. "The mother left a suicide 
note indicating this was best for the child and herself," he said. 
</P>
<P>
Lt. Richard Iddings said the handwritten note also asked for forgiveness from 
God and her family. 
</P>
<P>
At the time of the shooting, Rios and her daughter were riding in the back of a 
camper driven by Pasquale Buzzelli. Buzzelli told police that he was driving 
the two to his Panorama City house from East Los Angeles, where Rios was 
staying with members of her family. 
</P>
<P>
Rios and her daughter chose to ride in the back of the camper so they could 
sleep before a Halloween party at a local park, Lt. Richard Iddings said. 
</P>
<P>
As he passed Branford Park, Buzzelli said, he heard two sharp reports, seconds 
apart. He continued driving the few miles to his residence, however, because he 
thought the noises were backfires or Halloween revelers. 
</P>
<P>
But when he arrived home, Buzzelli found Rios and her daughter wounded. Rios 
apparently used a handgun that was kept in one of the camper's cabinets. 
Buzzelli had shown her how to use the gun the week before, Iddings said. 
</P>
<P>
Buzzelli shut the door and drove to Kaiser Permanente Medical Care Program in 
Panorama City. Samantha was pronounced dead on arrival at the hospital. Her 
mother died about four hours later. 
</P>
</TEXT>
