</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A 25-year-old construction worker suffered minor injuries Thursday after being 
trapped for more than two hours in a cave-in at a Glendale hotel construction 
site where a similar accident in August killed another worker. 
</P>
<P>
Two dozen firefighters and city crews worked carefully to free John Jehlik of 
Long Beach, who was trapped chest-deep in dirt at the bottom of a 15-foot-deep 
sinkhole on Glenoaks Boulevard. 
</P>
<P>
On Aug. 10, Enrique Ayala, a 33-year-old drilling company foreman, was buried 
head-first in another cave-in. A series of trenches is being dug alongside the 
Verdugo Wash and filled with concrete to anchor an 18-story Red Lion hotel. 
</P>
<P>
Cal/OSHA concluded that no negligence was involved in Ayala's death, said 
spokesman Rick Rice. But after sending two investigators to the scene Thursday, 
the state ordered the site closed until officials meet today with companies 
working on the project, Rice said. 
