<HEADLINE>
<P>
CELLULAR FIRM SET TO MARKET NEW PRODUCT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DEAN TAKAHASHI, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
ANAHEIM 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Universal Cellular Inc., a start-up cellular equipment manufacturer, plans to 
introduce a new product designed to compete with pocket-sized portable phone 
technology offered by several U.S. and Japanese companies. 
</P>
<P>
Universal Cellular said Thursday that it has awarded a $5-million advertising 
account to a Minneapolis ad agency, McElligott Wright Morrison White, which was 
founded recently by several former top executives at the Chiat/Day/Mojo agency 
in New York. 
</P>
<P>
Peter McCoy, vice president of marketing for Universal Cellular, said the 
company has also signed a joint-venture agreement with a "major" Japanese 
company to distribute the unidentified product outside North America. Motorola 
Inc., NEC Corp. and Mitsubishi Electric Corp. are the major manufacturers of 
pocket-size mobile phones. 
</P>
<P>
"We're ecstatic that MWMW has agreed to handle this account," McCoy said. "The 
amount shows that we're serious about the market." 
</P>
<P>
McCoy said the cellular product is a pocket-sized device "that is more than a 
phone." He said the company has been developing the proprietary cellular 
product for 18 months, but he declined to reveal more details about the 
product. 
</P>
<P>
Universal Cellular's chief executive is James Wohl, a cable television industry 
veteran and former president of West Hawaii Cable Vision Inc. 
</P>
<P>
"This is a tremendously exciting project for us," said Tony Wright, president 
of MWMW and an ad veteran who worked on the Energizer's popular Bunny 
advertising campaign. 
</P>
<P>
Wright said the Universal portable phones would compete with products in the 
emerging personal communications network market, a cellular technology that 
would enable cordless office phones to be taken outside the office. 
</P>
<P>
Such pocket phones could allow workers to travel large distances, such as to 
and from home, and be in constant contact with a telephone. 
</P>
<P>
The Anaheim firm said the product will be sold internationally and displayed at 
an industry trade show in January in Las Vegas. The product's introduction date 
has not been set. 
</P>
</TEXT>
